	<li class="comment odd alt depth-8" id="comment-12117" itemprop="comment" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Comment">
		<div id="div-comment-12117" class="comment-body">
		<div class="comment-author" itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
	<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/3f2bfad6bac969c8cf6624a7d4bc56eb?s=48&amp;d=retro&amp;r=X' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' />	<cite itemprop="name">Sander</cite> <span class="says">says:</span>	</div>

	<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a itemprop="url" href="http://ottopress.com/2012/making-a-custom-control-for-the-theme-customizer/comment-page-1/#comment-12117">
		<time itemprop="dateCreated" datetime="2013-10-30T17:59:36+00:00">October 30, 2013 at 5:59 pm</time></a>	</div>

	<div itemprop="text"><p>It shouldn&#8217;t be a problem. I use many sliders in my theme.</p>
<p>In my .js I do this:</p>
<p>HTML:<br />
<code><br />
&lt;input name=&quot;id; ?&gt;" type="text" link(); ?&gt; value="value(); ?&gt;" /&gt;</p>
<p></code></p>
<p>jQuery:<br />
<code><br />
$j('input[name="themex_options[main_page_width]"]').next('div.slider').slider({ *options* });<br />
</code></p>
<p>So I use the input field as selector and turn the div next to it into a slider. This way you always create an unique slider.</p>
<p>Hope this helps!</p>
</div>

	<div class="reply">
		</div>
		</div>
