	<li class="comment even depth-3" id="comment-11770" itemprop="comment" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Comment">
		<div id="div-comment-11770" class="comment-body">
		<div class="comment-author" itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
	<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/3f2bfad6bac969c8cf6624a7d4bc56eb?s=48&amp;d=retro&amp;r=X' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' />	<cite itemprop="name">Sander</cite> <span class="says">says:</span>	</div>

	<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a itemprop="url" href="http://ottopress.com/2012/making-a-custom-control-for-the-theme-customizer/comment-page-1/#comment-11770">
		<time itemprop="dateCreated" datetime="2013-04-15T06:58:53+00:00">April 15, 2013 at 6:58 am</time></a>	</div>

	<div itemprop="text"><p>After a good sleep and some thinking I&#8217;ve found the solution: my CSS is only generated when saving and publishing from the customizer. So there are no vars loaded and CSS generated on each page view. And that&#8217;s why Customizer can&#8217;t inject the changed values on refresh. </p>
<p>My solution is to generate dynamic CSS on each pageview, for Customizer only. <img src="http://ottopress.com/wp-content/plugins/classic-smilies/img/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" class="wp-smiley" /> </p>
</div>

